- Every Content Type has a "Sobject" (SiteObject), this is the unique identifier for the Content Type:

>> newsitem = News.find(:first)
=> #<News:0xb749db84>
>> newsitem.sobject
=> #<Sobject:0xb72fcdac>

- A Sobject can hold relations to other Sobjects. 

- These relations are "named", that is, you can qualify them with a category (= a label, tag)

- The relation database table looks like this: "id | from_sobject_id | to_sobject_id | category_id"

Operations
===========

General
-------
- objects used below:
>> category = Category.find_by_name("picture")
>> image = Image.find(:first)

Adding
------
We add a relation "picture" from a newsitem to an image :
>> newsitem.sobject.build_to_relations_as_from :to => image.sobject, :category => category

Or adding a relation "picture" from an image to a news item
>> image.sobject.build_to_relations_as_to :from => newsitem.sobject, :category => category

Removing
--------
Remove all relations for a content type
>> newsitem.sobject.relations_as_from.clear

Remove 1 relation for a content type
>> newsitem.sobject.relations_as_from.find_by_to_sobject_id_and_category_id(image.sobject.id,category.id).first.destroy

Remove all relations of type "picture"
>>newsitem.sobject.relations_as_from.find_by_category_id(category.id).each { |rel| rel.destroy }




